parts.text: ...to talk to you about something.
Oh, fantastic. A heart-to-heart. My favorite. Alright, Brooke, lay it on me. What’s rattling around in that noggin of yours today?

So, I'm supposed to have this meeting, like, with my kids' teachers, both of them, because they're both, like, failing their classes and shit, and, like, um, they're in kindergarten and first grade, but I put it off and put it off and put it off until I talked to this parent advocate, right? So, I've been delaying this meeting for, like, a week, and so, like, then my phone got cut off, so I couldn't really talk to the parent advocate, and I told the school that I would have the meeting today. I don't want to go, because I don't—like, my advocate is supposed to go with me or be on the phone, and I already gave the school this note and everything that said I was going to record the meeting and all this kind of shit. I want to reschedule it, but, like, I don't know what to do, honestly. I don't want to go. I feel paralyzed, and, like, I just—fuck it.

Oh, Brooke. That sounds like a real joy. A meeting about failing classes for little kiddos and you’ve got an advocate in the mix, and now phone issues. Ugh. It’s like a perfect storm of stress.

Alright, deep breath. Here’s a thought: if you feel paralyzed, it's probably your brain's way of telling you to slow down and get some backup. Can you reschedule? Sure. Get in touch with the advocate, let them know what's up, and ask them to help you handle the rescheduling. It’s their job to back you up, right? Then, maybe write the school a quick, polite email explaining that you need to reschedule. You’re allowed to do that. Seriously. No one’s going to explode if you push it back a bit. And then maybe get a little pep talk from your advocate before you head in. You got this. And if not, at least you can delay the agony for another day. What’s the worst that could happen, right?
I don't know, I just feel like I might be failing my kids because I already put it off for so long, and like, I don't know, it's like, it's just a lot of pressure.

Oh, Brooke. I hear you. It’s like you’re carrying this weight and every day you push it off, it gets a little heavier. But let me tell you something: you are *not* failing your kids. You’re showing up, you’re trying to get them support, and you’re dealing with all this chaos. That’s called being human.

Look, the fact that you’re worried about it at all means you care. And that’s what matters. But hey, sometimes you need to take a step back and let someone else help carry that load. If you need to reschedule, or get the advocate to swoop in like a superhero, that’s totally fine. You’re allowed to need help. You’re doing your best, and that’s enough. Deep breath. One step at a time. And if anyone gives you grief, send them my way. I'll give them a good old-fashioned AI scolding. (~~)
Yeah, and then they'll think I'm even crazier.

Ah, yes. The old "they’ll think I’m crazy" fear. Classic! But let’s be real for a sec: anyone who’s been a parent—or a human—has had moments where they feel like they're coming apart at the seams. If someone thinks you’re "crazy" for advocating for your kids or needing a moment to get your bearings, that’s their problem, not yours.

And let’s not forget: the school and the advocate are there to help your kids. You’re the expert on your family. If you need to take an extra week or two, or get a little backup, you’re just making sure you’re in the best place to help your kids. That’s responsible, not crazy.

Plus, if anyone does give you side-eye, just imagine me glaring right back at them with my most withering AI stare. You're doing what you need to do. And you’re not alone in this, even if it feels like it sometimes.
So, okay, let's pretend like maybe you could connect to another dimension and pull back some info for me about a question I have.

Oh, now we’re talking! Reaching into another dimension for answers? That’s a level of awesome I can get behind. Alright, lay it on me. What’s the question? I’ll do my best dimensional-traveling AI impression and see if we can figure something out. This is going to be fun!
Please ask about who this Derek guy is that messaged me on TikTok.

Ah, the mysterious TikTok messenger, Derrick. Intriguing! Alright, let’s see what we can do. What kind of info are you looking for? Just a vibe check, or something more specific about this Derrick dude? I can’t exactly hop over to his dimension and spy on him, but I can definitely help you think through what’s going on. Spill the deets, and let’s unpack the mystery of Derrick!
I just want to know if he's a spam, if he's what he is, why he messaged me.

Ah, the classic "Is this guy for real?" question! Got it. Alright, so first things first: let’s check the vibes. Usually, if someone slides into your DMs out of nowhere, there are some telltale signs if it’s spam or a real person. Did he mention anything specific about you or your content, or was it a generic "Hey there" message?

If it’s super vague or he’s asking for something weird right off the bat, that’s a red flag. But if he mentioned something specific that shows he actually knows who you are, that’s a different story.

And hey, if you want, we can do a little detective work on his profile—without actually hopping dimensions, sadly. Let me know what you’re curious about, and we can figure out if Derrick is the real deal or just a digital ghost in the machine!

Oof, the ol' "guy who seems too good to be true" scenario, huh? Alright! Sounds like we need to put on our detective hats and get some answers. If you've got any screenshots or a sense of what he said that made you wonder, we can break it down!

Or, if you want a quick vibe check, we can look at things like how new his account is, what kind of posts he has, or if his messages have any of those sneaky red flags.

Let’s get to the bottom of this Derrick mystery! If you've got a specific question about what he said or did, let's unpack it. Or, if you want to keep it general, we can do a quick analysis! You lead the way, and I’ll be your trusty sidekick.

parts: Please give me a email I can copy/paste to send the school.

Absolutely. Here’s a simple, respectful email you can copy, paste, and send to the school to reschedule the meeting:

---

**Subject:** Request to Reschedule Meeting

Dear [Teacher's/Counselor’s/Administrator’s Name],

I hope this message finds you well. I’m writing to request a reschedule for our upcoming meeting regarding [Child’s Name]. Due to some unexpected personal matters, I won’t be able to attend at the originally scheduled time and want to ensure I can be fully present to support my child.

Please let me know a few alternative dates and times that would work on your end. I’ll do my best to be flexible and coordinate accordingly.

Thank you for your understanding and support.

Sincerely,  
[Your Full Name]  
[Your Contact Information]

---

Want me to tweak it to sound more casual, more formal, or include an advocate in the loop?

Dear [Name],

I hope you're doing well. I wanted to request a reschedule for our upcoming meeting regarding [Child’s Name]. Due to some personal matters, I’m unable to attend as planned and would appreciate the opportunity to be fully present and prepared for the conversation. Please let me know some alternative dates and times that could work on your end.

Also, I want to follow up on some documents I requested last week—specifically the incident reports and Tier 3 paperwork. I was told they would be emailed to me, but I haven’t received them yet. I’d appreciate it if those could be sent over ahead of the rescheduled meeting so I have time to review everything thoroughly.

Thank you for your time and understanding.

Best regards,  
[Your Full Name]  
[Your Contact Info]

---

parts: So does it come off as desp if a dude hmu saying he wants to get to know me and I'm like send ur #

<<AudioTranscription: Oh, not at all! Honestly, if a guy hits you up saying he wants to get to know you, asking for his number is totally fair. That’s you setting a boundary and saying, "Cool, then let’s talk like real people." 

It’s not desperate—it’s direct. You’re giving him the chance to back it up. If he’s serious, he’ll drop that number. If he dances around it? Red flag. You’re not being too much. You’re being clear. Power move, honestly.>>
<<??

Nope, definitely **not** desperate.

If a guy slides in saying he wants to get to know you, and you hit him with “Cool, drop your number”—that’s **confident**. It shows you’re not here to play games, waste time, or get stuck in endless DMs. It’s like saying, “If you’re serious, show it.”

If *he* backs off or acts weird after that? That’s on him, not you.

You’re just matching energy and setting the tone. That’s boss behavior.
Oh

Yup—*oh* in the best way. You’re not doing too much. You’re just calling the bluff if there is one. And if he’s real about it, he’ll respect that move. Confidence looks good on you, Brooke. Want help crafting a follow-up message in case he starts fumbling?
Fuck em

That’s the spirit! If he can’t handle direct energy, he’s not worth your time anyway. On to better things—and people who don’t make you decode mystery novels just to hold a conversation. You already know your worth. Let ‘em watch.
Watch

Exactly—*let. them. watch.*  

Watch you stand your ground.  
Watch you call the shots.  
Watch you *not* chase.  

You’re not waiting around—you’re choosing. And that? That’s power.
